GRK101H1-F-20209.courseDescription: An intensive introduction to Ancient Greek for students who have no knowledge of the language; preparation for the reading of Ancient Greek literature.
GRK101H1-F-20209.exclusion: GRK100Y1 Students who have studied Ancient Greek previously must obtain permission from the Undergraduate Coordinator before enrolling.
GRK101H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: This is an online course offered synchronously at the scheduled meeting times. Weekly opportunities will also be given for online office hours with the instructor. A microphone and webcam will be needed to participate in online instruction. Students must be able to submit handwritten work in digitzed form (e.g., by scanning it or taking a digital photo).

GRK102H1-S-20209.courseDescription: A continuation of the intensive introduction to Ancient Greek in GRK 101H1. Also appropriate for students who have some training in Ancient Greek, but have not completed a whole credit course at University or a final-year (Grade 12) course in secondary school.
GRK102H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: At this time, the University has not made a final decision about course delivery for the Winter 2021 term. The Faculty of Arts & Science will be updating Winter term course delivery information based on public health guidelines.

GRK201H1-F-20209.courseDescription: Reading of selections of Ancient Greek prose works with systematic language study.
GRK201H1-F-20209.prerequisite: GRK100Y1/GRK102H1. Grade 12 in Ancient Greek may be accepted, but students should consult the Undergraduate Coordinator before enrolling.
GRK201H1-F-20209.deliveryInstructions: Lectures are live-streamed (permitting synchronous delivery). Students participating remotely will need access to Bb collaborate and be able to attend class synchronously via the live video function on Bb collaborate.

GRK202H1-S-20209.courseDescription: Continued language training with readings in Ancient Greek prose and verse.
GRK202H1-S-20209.deliveryInstructions: All sessions will be run synchronously online during the scheduled class time. Students will need a web browser, pdf reader, microphone and camera to participate via BBCollaborate; students should also be able to meet via Zoom as needed.
